    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 6, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🛩️ The Second F-15E Crew Member Was Rescued. Inside Iran.\n\nAfter days of uncertainty, US special operations forces recovered the second crew member of the F-15E shot down on April 3 — in a complex mission on Iranian soil.\n\n- **The rescue:** Both crew members of the downed F-15E have now been recovered. The war is in its 38th day. At least 2,076 Iranians have been killed, 26,500 wounded.\n- **The scale:** Iran's Science Minister reports that over 30 universities have been struck by the US-Israel air campaign. \"Going very well\" is still the White House's characterization.\n\n*Two pilots recovered. One from inside Iran via special operations. The White House's PR strategy is doing heavy lifting.*\n\n**Sources:** [NPR](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/04/nx-s1-5773436/iran-war-updates) | [Al Jazeera](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/liveblog/2026/4/2/iran-war-live-trump-to-address-nation-tehran-denies-seeking-ceasefire)\n\n---\n\n## 🛡️ UAE Intercepted 23 Missiles and 56 Drones. The Petrochemical Plant Burned Anyway.\n\nThe UAE shot down almost everything Iran launched on April 4. The debris from the things it shot down caught a petrochemical plant on fire.\n\n- **The intercepts:** 23 ballistic missiles and 56 UAVs intercepted by UAE air defenses on April 4. Technically a success.\n- **The debris:** Falling fragments started fires at the Borouge petrochemicals plant on April 5 and damaged gas facilities in Habshan and Ajban. One person killed. Iran's position is that if you intercept enough missiles, the physics still wins eventually.\n\n*Intercepting 79 incoming weapons and still getting a petrochemical plant fire is a good argument for not being in a ballistic missile conflict.*\n\n**Sources:** [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2026_Iranian_strikes_on_the_United_Arab_Emirates) | [Al Jazeera](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/3/12/iran-targets-gulf-nations-with-missiles-drones-as-oil-prices-soar)\n\n---\n\n## ⛽ Europe's Gas Reserves Will Hit Zero by April 20\n\nThe Strait of Hormuz has been 87% blocked since mid-March. Europe started the spring at 30% gas capacity after a bad winter. The math is not going well.\n\n- **The projection:** EU fuel reserves are forecast to be fully depleted by April 20 if the Hormuz closure holds. Dutch TTF gas benchmarks have nearly doubled to over €60/MWh.\n- **The problem:** Qatar suspended LNG exports simultaneously. Europe's short-term alternatives are limited. The IEA has already called this the worst oil supply shock in the history of the global oil market.\n\n*The calendar says April 20. The gas reserves say April 20. Both statements are equally alarming.*\n\n**Sources:** [Pravda EU](https://eu.news-pravda.com/world/2026/04/04/183562.html) | [Wikipedia — Economic impact](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_impact_of_the_2026_Iran_war)\n\n---\n\n## 🔧 Trump's Tariffs on Steel, Aluminum and Copper Just Got Bigger. Today.\n\nNew Section 232 rules took effect this morning — and the change isn't subtle.\n\n- **What changed:** Tariffs now apply to the full customs value of goods made substantially from steel, aluminum, or copper — not just the declared metal content. Flat rate: 50% for goods made almost entirely of these metals, 25% for derivatives. Pharmaceutical tariffs of up to 100% were also announced on what the White House is calling \"Liberation Day's anniversary.\"\n- **The scope:** Over 50 different trade policy changes in one year. The Supreme Court's February IEEPA ruling is now generating legal challenges to the entire tariff architecture. The administration is doubling down anyway.\n\n*\"Liberation Day\" was apparently so liberating they made an anniversary out of it.*\n\n**Sources:** [White House](https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/04/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-strengthens-tariffs-on-steel-aluminum-and-copper-imports/) | [GEODIS](https://geodis.com/us-en/resources/customs-corner/united-states-announces-changes-section-232-steel-aluminum-and-copper)\n\n---\n\n## 🤝 Congress Wants Nvidia's Blackwell Chips Classified as Weapons\n\nThe House Foreign Affairs Committee advanced the AI OVERWATCH Act this week — a bill that would require Congressional approval before selling advanced AI chips abroad, like an arms deal.\n\n- **The mechanism:** Nvidia Blackwell chips would require Congressional notification before export, and would be banned outright to \"foreign entities of concern\" for two years. A companion MATCH Act would ban export of key AI chipmaking machinery to China.\n- **The context:** The BIS already shifted chip export policy to China from automatic denial to case-by-case review. Congress would like that to go the other direction. Nvidia's stock has opinions about this.\n\n*The US government would like to regulate AI chips the same way it regulates cruise missiles. Nvidia would like to sell them to everyone. Classic.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/03/05/us-reportedly-considering-sweeping-new-chip-export-controls/) | [ML Strategies](https://www.mlstrategies.com/insights-center/viewpoints/54031/2026-02-04-_026-ai-policy-and-semiconductor-outlook-how-federal)"
  }
